 France":"Le Hamel, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"en","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 任, based on its Mandarin pronunciation, see   Ren   1.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 全, based on its pronunciation in Shanghai dialect, see   Quan   2.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 曾, see   Zeng  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ren","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Yong, Hong, Hui, Chuan, Gang, Guang, Jian, Liang, Lihua, Ning, Qing, Chang, Min, Shen, Yiming.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 任, a term for women's rank of peerage in ancient Chinese: (i) it is said that the surname can be traced back to one of the 25 sons of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). (ii) from Ren (任), the name of an ancient state (located in Renxian in Hebei province) granted to Yu Yang, said to be a son or grandson of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). His descendants adopted the name of the state as their surname. (iii) from Ren (任), the name of a state (located in Shandong province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","English: variant of   Renn   2."]}]},{"name":"Santerre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Ovila, Pierre.","French: habitational name from a region in Picardy, located to the southeast of the Somme river, named with Latin <i>sana terra</i> ‘healthy, wholesome land’, and perhaps also from Le Santerre, the name of several places in the northern part of France."],"variants":[]},{"name":"François","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval name meaning ‘French’.  See  <b>Francis</b>   . Its popularity in France has been greatly influenced by Italian <i>Francesco</i> and the fame of St Francis of Assisi."],"variants":[]},{"name":"1er","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian vernacular form of   Peter ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When François 1er de Rosières en Santerre was born in 1184, in Rosières-en-Santerre, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Robert II de Rosières-en-Santerre Chevalier Croisé, was 31 and his mother,